<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-491-886  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 491 886.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 28 1990 v24 n22 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Keeping track of the Earth's health. (new storage method formassive files of environmental data)(includes related article onnominees for Computerworld Smithsonian Awards)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilder, Clinton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Center for Atmospheric Research (NCAR) has beennominated for one of the annual Computerworld Smithsonian Awardsbecause of NCAR's data storage system designed to store massivefiles of environmental data that aids greenhouse-effectresearchers.andP;  The agency's file handling system is designed forits Cray Research Inc supercomputers that bypasses transfer pointsin a typical supercomputer file system.andP;  Users can directly accessfile in the mass-storage controller, rather than the controllersending files to a network node and then to the supercomputer.andP;  Anelectronic file directory on the controller creates a hierarchy offiles, making the system possible.andP;  According to Bill Buzbee,NCAR's director of scientific computing, better ability tomanipulate massive files is essential to climate change research,which includes research into the much-talked-about 'greenhouseeffect.'andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. National Center for Atmospheric ResearchEnvironmental ProtectionInformation Storage and RetrievalAchievements and AwardsMass MemoryHierarchical OrganizationFile ManagementAccess MethodsSupercomputersComputerworld Smithsonian AwardsEnvironmental protection.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>